I'm not sure is any hard or fast rules of etiquette, but there are a couple I follow.

1. Don't be needy and desperate regarding really popular people. If Josh Lee Kwai or the Prof is asking for input or makes a tweet that you have something substantive to add, do it. But don't be that guy who has to reply with some inane bullshit to every single tweet that a popular person makes.
Depends. If they're a content creator and I notice I'll add them. If not, I usually sont follow back

2. Dont' be needy and desperate regarding women in Magic. If someone is asking for input or makes a tweet that you have something substantive to add, do it. But don't be that guy who follows every single woman in Magic on twitter and replies to every single tweet they make telling them how pretty their eyes are or how great their cosplay is.
So Rachel Agnes' followers?
I'm not going to get that specific, lol. Just don't be creepy or desperate or weird and you'll be fine. I know that seems like a low bar to clear, but a whole lot of people don't clear it.

I would just say plug your own stuff when appropriate and build up other's stuff more than you do your own. If you can get people noticing and returning the favor it'll give you more reach than you can get on your own

text: Pretty sure I can avoid creepy and desperate. Weird? Well...

I'm in a discussion elsewhere about Bernie Sanders, which then popped a third rule into my head; give, don't just take. Retweet other people's stuff, make positive comments, make useful posts, etc. Put productive things out there. Don't just make everything about you all the time. People will care about your stuff if they think you care about theirs. They won't if they think you only care about your stuff.
